d_year":1840,"notes":"Served during winter 1839-40."},{"role":"Businessman","organization":"Kellogg & Strong Steamboat Company and Warehouse, Milwaukee","notes":"Prominent Milwaukee merchant."},{"role":"Manager","organization":"Newberry Furnace Company"}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["wisconsin_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Helped secure the land for Forest Home Cemetery","body":"Robert Hunter Strong was instrumental in securing the land for Forest Home Cemetery in Milwaukee and persuading St. Paul's Episcopal Church to establish the cemetery there — a civic contribution that anchored Milwaukee's most prominent burial ground. He came to Wisconsin around 1830, clerked in the territorial legislature in 1839-40, built his fortune through the Kellogg & Strong Steamboat company and Newberry Furnace, and was twice married."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Bridged two Strong-Hooker marriages and two frontier states","body":"Robert Hunter Strong was the son of the second Strong-Hooker marriage — Judge Elisha Beebe Strong and Dolly Goodwin Hooker — and the father of the man who would carry that name to a third generation: Beebe Hooker Strong, born Milwaukee 1866. He came to Wisconsin around 1830 at age ten, making the journey from the Rochester land grants his father had built to the Great Lakes frontier, and with him the Strong-Hooker legacy crossed into a new American West."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Edward Hooker, Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker (1909)","url":"https://archive.org/details/descendantsofrev00hook"},{"label":"History of Descendants of Elder John Strong, Vol. 1 (1871)","url":"https://dn720908.ca.archive.org/0/items/historyofdescend0001dwig/historyofdescend0001dwig.pdf"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"robert-strong-1820"},"I00916":{"id":"I00916","former_ids":[],"is_plac